\section{Structural commentary}
The compound $\mathrm{Na}_{5} \mathrm{H}\left(\mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\right)_{2}$ was unexpectedly synthesized by heating $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{1.5}$. The asymmetric unit of the title compound is shown in Fig. 1. The root-mean-square deviation of the non-hydrogen atoms in the Rietveld-refined and DFT-optimized structures is $0.216 \AA$ (Fig. 2). The reasonable agreement between the two structures is evidence that the experimental structure is correct (van de Streek \& Neumann, 2014). This discussion uses the DFT-optimized structure. Most of the bond lengths, bond angles, and torsion angles fall within the normal ranges indicated by a Mercury Mogul geometry check (Macrae et al., 2008). Both the O28$\mathrm{C} 10$ bond length of $1.249 \AA[Z$-score $=3.4$; average $=$ $1.213(13) \AA$ ] and the $\mathrm{O} 28-\mathrm{C} 10-\mathrm{C} 8$ angle of $120.4^{\circ}$ [Z-score $=4.0$; average $\left.=126.9(16)^{\circ}\right]$ are flagged as unusual. Since this oxygen atom also coordinates to an $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$cation, it is not unreasonable to encounter some slightly unusual geometry. Each $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$cation is chelated by at least one citrate anion. The chelation modes include hydroxyl/terminal carboxyl, terminal/ central carboxyl, and coordination of both oxygen atoms of a terminal carboxyl group.

The structure contains five independent $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$cations. $\mathrm{Na} 37$, Na38, Na39, and $\mathrm{Na} 40$ exhibit octahedral coordination spheres, with bond-valence sums of $1.19,1.24,1.04$, and $1.17$

